				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">It would work as long as you could come up with a Game Genie patch that causes execution of SRAM. Run game in debugger to find when it first enables SRAM, then find a JMP/JSR instruction close thereafter and patch its high byte to $60, then have SRAM with page $60 filled with $EA, and the boot loader beginning on the next page. For vector overrides, you can do the same; patch the high bytes to $07, then put JMP instructions where they happen to point in page 7 of RAM. The above would nicely fit in three Game Genie patch slots as well.
<br />
<br />The main snag is that you need to find some way to initially get the boot loader into SRAM. If you could have someone put it on an EPROM and replace the ROM with that, then you'd have a really cheap devcart. Of course if you're going to the trouble of replacing the ROM, you might as well put a Flash ROM there instead, as it's virtually the same amount of rewiring and chip cost.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

